# TypeScript Standards

## Strict Mode (Always On)

```json
// tsconfig.json - NON-NEGOTIABLE
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "strict": true,
    "noUnusedLocals": true,
    "noUnusedParameters": true,
    "noFallthroughCasesInSwitch": true
  }
}
```

## Type Inference vs Explicit Types

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Let TypeScript infer when obvious
const count = 0; // inferred as number
const users = await db.query.users.findMany(); // inferred from Drizzle

// ✅ GOOD - Explicit for function returns (public API)
export function calculateCredits(tokens: number): number {
  return Math.ceil(tokens * 0.02);
}

// ✅ GOOD - Explicit for complex objects
interface UserProfile {
  id: string;
  email: string;
  tier: "free" | "pro" | "premium" | "ultra";
  credits: number;
}

const profile: UserProfile = {
  id: "123",
  email: "user@example.com",
  tier: "free",
  credits: 50000,
};

// ❌ BAD - Redundant annotation
const count: number = 0; // TypeScript already knows!
```

## Discriminated Unions for State

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Impossible to have invalid state
type ApiState<T> =
  | { status: "idle" }
  | { status: "loading" }
  | { status: "error"; error: string }
  | { status: "success"; data: T };

function ChatMessages({ state }: { state: ApiState<Message[]> }) {
  switch (state.status) {
    case "loading":
      return <Spinner />;
    case "error":
      return <Error message={state.error} />; // TS knows error exists
    case "success":
      return <List items={state.data} />; // TS knows data exists
    case "idle":
      return null;
  }
}

// ❌ BAD - Can have contradictory state
type ApiState<T> = {
  loading: boolean;
  error?: string;
  data?: T;
}; // Can have loading=true AND data at same time!
```

## Zod for Runtime Validation

```typescript
import { z } from "zod";

// ✅ GOOD - Validate untrusted input (API, user input)
const createChatSchema = z.object({
  title: z.string().min(1).max(100),
  userId: z.string().uuid(),
});

export async function POST(request: Request) {
  const body = await request.json();
  const parsed = createChatSchema.safeParse(body);

  if (!parsed.success) {
    return Response.json({ error: parsed.error.flatten() }, { status: 400 });
  }

  // TypeScript knows: parsed.data has correct shape
  const chat = await db.insert(chats).values(parsed.data);
}

// ✅ GOOD - Infer types from Zod schemas
type CreateChatInput = z.infer<typeof createChatSchema>;

// ❌ BAD - Manual validation (error-prone)
if (typeof body.title !== "string" || body.title.length > 100) {
  // Easy to miss cases
}
```

## Type Utilities

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Use built-in utilities
type User = { id: string; email: string; password: string };
type PublicUser = Omit<User, "password">;
type PartialUser = Partial<User>;
type RequiredEmail = Pick<User, "email">;

// ✅ GOOD - Drizzle type inference
import type { InferSelectModel, InferInsertModel } from "drizzle-orm";
import { users } from "./schema";

export type User = InferSelectModel<typeof users>;
export type NewUser = InferInsertModel<typeof users>;

// ❌ BAD - Duplicating types
type User = { id: string; email: string };
type PublicUser = { id: string; email: string }; // Duplicate!
```

## Generics for Reusability

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Generic API response type
interface ApiResponse<T> {
  data?: T;
  error?: string;
  code?: string;
}

async function fetchApi<T>(url: string): Promise<ApiResponse<T>> {
  const response = await fetch(url);
  return response.json();
}

// Usage - full type safety
const result = await fetchApi<Message[]>("/api/messages");
if (result.data) {
  result.data.forEach((msg) => console.log(msg.content)); // TS knows structure
}

// ✅ GOOD - Generic React component
interface ListProps<T> {
  items: T[];
  renderItem: (item: T) => React.ReactNode;
}

function List<T>({ items, renderItem }: ListProps<T>) {
  return <div>{items.map(renderItem)}</div>;
}
```

## Enums vs Union Types

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - String union (preferred)
type Tier = "free" | "pro" | "premium" | "ultra";

// ❌ AVOID - Enums (unnecessary complexity)
enum Tier {
  Free = "free",
  Pro = "pro",
}

// ✅ GOOD - Const object for values + types
export const TIERS = {
  free: "free",
  pro: "pro",
  premium: "premium",
  ultra: "ultra",
} as const;

export type Tier = (typeof TIERS)[keyof typeof TIERS];
```

## Function Types

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Explicit function signature
type OnSendMessage = (content: string) => Promise<void>;

interface ChatInputProps {
  onSend: OnSendMessage;
}

// ✅ GOOD - Arrow function with inline types
const handleSend = async (content: string): Promise<void> => {
  await api.sendMessage(content);
};

// ❌ BAD - any type
const handleSend = async (content: any) => {}; // Never use any!
```

## Readonly for Immutability

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Readonly arrays
function ChatMessages({ messages }: { messages: readonly Message[] }) {
  // messages.push() // Error! Can't mutate
  return messages.map((m) => <ChatMessage key={m.id} message={m} />);
}

// ✅ GOOD - Readonly object properties
interface Config {
  readonly apiKey: string;
  readonly baseUrl: string;
}
```

## Type Guards

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Type guard function
function isError(
  response: ApiResponse<unknown>
): response is { error: string } {
  return "error" in response && typeof response.error === "string";
}

if (isError(response)) {
  console.error(response.error); // TS knows error exists
}

// ✅ GOOD - Discriminated union (automatic type guard)
function handleState(state: ApiState<Message[]>) {
  if (state.status === "error") {
    console.error(state.error); // TS automatically narrows
  }
}
```

## Module Organization

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD - Export types from shared package
// apps/shared/types/index.ts
export type { User, Chat, Message };
export type { ApiResponse, ApiError };

// apps/sidepanel/src/hooks/useChat.ts
import type { Message } from "@prophet/shared";
```

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

- ❌ Using `any` (use `unknown` if truly unknown)
- ❌ Using `as` assertions (fix the types instead)
- ❌ Disabling strict mode
- ❌ `@ts-ignore` comments (fix the issue)
- ❌ Empty interfaces (use type)
- ❌ Enums (use const objects + type unions)
- ❌ Optional chaining abuse (`a?.b?.c?.d`)
- ❌ Non-null assertions (`value!`) unless 100% sure

## Quick Checklist

- [ ] Strict mode enabled
- [ ] Public functions have explicit return types
- [ ] Runtime validation with Zod for external data
- [ ] Discriminated unions for complex states
- [ ] No `any` types
- [ ] No `@ts-ignore` comments
- [ ] Types exported from shared package
